record_data.record_plain_text: 2. APPLICABILITY This Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff applies to the resale, reassignment or transfer of Transmission Rights only on those Transmission Systems where the owner, operator or controller has elected not to adopt Section 23 of the Commission’s pro forma Open Access Transmission Tariff. This Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff has no applicability to assignments of network transmission service.

4. SERVICE AGREEMENT Service under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff is available pursuant to a Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement. Terms may be agreed to orally or may be recorded in a letter or transaction record separately from the Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement. If reduced to writing, such letter or memorandum will be filed with the Commission only upon a special request of a party or the Commission, but would not ordinarily be filed as a precondition of service.

6. WAIVERS Any waiver at any time by any party of its rights with respect to a default or breach of any obligation under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff or any other matter shall not be deemed a waiver with respect to any subsequent default or breach of any obligation of the same or any other matter.

5. UNCONTROLLABLE FORCES No party shall be considered to be in default or in breach of any of its obligations under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff (except to make payment as specified) when a failure of performance shall be due to an uncontrollable force. The term “uncontrollable force” means any cause beyond the control of the party affected, including but not restricted to failure of or threat of failure of facilities, flood, drought, earthquake, storm, fire, lightning, epidemic war, riot, civil disturbance or disobedience, labor dispute, labor or material shortage, sabotage, restraint by court order or public authority, or action or non-action by or failure to obtain the necessary authorizations or approvals from any governmental agency or authority which by exercise of due diligence such party could not reasonably have been expected to avoid and which by exercise of due diligence it has been unable to overcome. No party shall, however, be relieved pursuant to this Section 5 of liability for failure of performance to the extent that such failure is due to removable or remediable causes which it fails to remove or remedy within a reasonable time period. Nothing contained in this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff shall be construed to require a party to settle any strike or labor dispute in which it may be involved. Any party rendered unable to fulfill any of its obligations by reason of an uncontrollable force shall give prompt written notice of such fact to the other party and shall exercise due diligence to remove such inability within a reasonable time period.

Puget Sound Energy, Inc. Exhibit A Form of Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement for the FERC Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff This Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement, dated as of __________________, is entered into, by and between Puget Sound Energy, Inc. (“PSE”) and __________________ (“Customer”). PSE and Customer may also be referred to collectively as “Parties,” and individually as “Party.” PSE agrees to furnish and Customer agrees to purchase Transmission Rights pursuant to the terms and conditions of PSE’s FERC Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff as revised from time to time pursuant to filings with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1. With regard to Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider, Customer attests that it is an Eligible Customer as defined in the Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff. Customer will take all necessary steps to maintain its status as an Eligible Customer, and will inform PSE immediately as to any change in status. 2. This Agreement shall extend for __________________ from the date hereof, and shall continue in force thereafter until and unless canceled upon a minimum of 7 days prior written notice by either Party to the other Party. However, resales, reassignments or transfers already entered into prior to notice of termination shall continue for the duration of the resale, reassignment or transfer. 3. At the time of entering into a resale, reassignment or transfer of Transmission Rights, the Parties shall identify and document the agreed to type of transmission service to be provided hereunder/ 4. For each transaction, terms may be agreed to orally or may be recorded in a letter or transaction record separately from this Agreement. In addition, for each transaction, Customer shall pay to PSE such charges at are agreed upon orally, or, if expressly required by either Party with respect to a particular transaction, in writing. Each party consents to the recording of all telephone conversations relating to transactions under this agreement between its trading and marketing employees and the trading and marketing employees of the other Party, and that any such recordings will be retained in confidence, secured from improper access, and may be submitted in evidence in any proceeding or action relating to this agreement. With respect to such recordings, each Party waives any further notice of such monitoring or recording, and agrees to notify its employees of such monitoring or recording and to obtain any necessary consent of such employees. The recording, and the terms and conditions described therein, shall be the controlling evidence of the Parties’ agreement with respect to a particular transaction. 5. Any notice made to or by either Party regarding this Service Agreement shall be made to the representative of the other Party as indicated below. Puget Sound Energy, Inc. Customer IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this Service Agreement to be executed by their respective authorized officials. PUGET SOUND ENERGY, INC. 1. AVAILABILITY This Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff governs the resale, reassignment or transfer of Transmission Rights held by PSE’s Wholesale Merchant Function on the Transmission Systems of Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Providers. The Wholesale Merchant Function may resell, reassign, or transfer to a Customer, pursuant to an agreement negotiated between the Wholesale Merchant Function and said Customer, all or a portion of the Wholesale Merchant Function’s rights to the use of the Transmission System of a Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider that the Wholesale Merchant Function has reserved for its own use under a service agreement with the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider or has acquired from another customer of the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider.

FERC ELECTRIC TRANSMISSION REASSIGNMENT TARIFF FIRST REVISED VOLUME NO. 449 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS 0. DEFINITIONS 0.1 Commission: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 0.2 Customer: Any person or entity that desires to take transmission rights under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff executes a Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement, and is an Eligible Customer. 0.3 Eligible Customer: A person or entity that has a currently effective service agreement under the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider’s Open Access Transmission Tariff or other rate schedule or agreement pursuant to which the Transmission Rights to be transferred to Customer were originally obtained from the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider. The service agreement must be executed prior to the date on which the reassigned service commences. 0.4 Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff: PSE’s currently effective FERC Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff. 0.5 Open Access Transmission Tariff: Currently effective transmission tariff for non-discriminatory service. 0.6 PSE: Puget Sound Energy, Inc. 0.7 Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider: For the purposes of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, an entity that is not subject to the Commission’s jurisdiction and that is providing transmission of electrical energy in interstate commerce on its Transmission System but has not adopted Section 23 of the Commission’s pro forma Open Access Transmission Tariff. 0.8 Transmission Rights: Wholesale Merchant Function’s rights to the use of the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider Transmission System that the Wholesale Merchant Function has reserved for its own use under a service agreement with the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider. 0.9 Transmission System: The facilities used to transmit electrical energy in interstate commerce owned, operated and controlled by the Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider. 0.10 Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement: The agreement, and any amendments or supplements thereto, entered into by Customer for service under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff. A copy of the Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement is attached hereto as Exhibit A. 0.11 Wholesale Merchant Function: Employees whose responsibilities include sale for resale, or purchase for resale, of electric energy in interstate commerce and the resale, reassignment or transfer of Transmission Rights.

7. NOTICES 7.1 Any formal notice, demand or request shall be in writing and shall be deemed properly served, given or made if delivered in person, or upon receipt when sent by either registered or certified mail, postage prepaid, or by telecopy. Any such notice, demand or request directed to PSE shall be addressed to: Puget Sound Energy, Inc. P.O. Box 97034 Bellevue, WA 98009-9734 Attn: Manager Power Supply Operations Any such notice to a Customer under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff shall be addressed to the person and address shown on the service agreement. 7.2 The designation of the above persons or the address of any such person, may be changed at any time by notice given in the same manner as provided for other notices.

16. TERM The term of any transaction entered into under a Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement shall be specified in the Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement and shall not exceed thirty-six (36) months from the date the service is initiated.

15. LIABILITY Subject to applicable state and federal law which specifically limits a patty’s ability to enter into this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff no party, its directors, members of its governing body, officers or employees, shall be liable to any other party for any loss or damage to property, loss of earnings or revenues, personal injury, or any other direct, indirect, or consequential damages or injury which may occur or result from the performance or nonperformance of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff (including, but not limited to, any applicable Transmission Reassignment Service Agreement or transaction under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff), including, but not limited to, any liability arising as a result of any negligence of such party, its directors, members of its governing body, officers or employees, except to the extent such liability was caused by or resulted from an action taken or not taken by such parry at the direction of its directors, members of its governing body, its officers or employees with management or administrative responsibility affecting its performance under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, which is knowingly or intentionally taken or not taken with conscious indifference to the consequences thereof or with intent that injury or damage would result or would probably result therefrom.

14. THIRD PARTY BENEFICIARY This Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff shall not be construed to create rights in, or to grant remedies to, any third party as s beneficiary of any duty, obligation or undertaking established in this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff.

19. MODIFICATIONS PSE may unilaterally apply to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff under section 205 of the Federal Power Act and the regulations promulgated under that Act.

18. GOVERNING LAW This Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff shall be interpreted, construed and enforced in accordance with the laws of the State of Washington or the laws of the United States of America, whichever are applicable, as if executed and to be performed wholly within the State of Washington by citizens of that state, without reference to any rules regarding conflict of laws.

17. TERMINATION PSE shall have the unilateral right to terminate this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff at any time by filing with the Commission a notice of termination; provided, however, that any obligations incurred under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff; including transactions that extend beyond the termination of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, shall be preserved until satisfied. In the event that Customer no longer qualifies as an Eligible Customer, this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, and any underlying transactions, will terminate immediately; however, PSE, in its discretion, may give Customer an opportunity to restore its status as an Eligible Customer in order to avoid termination under this provision.

10. TRANSFER OF INTEREST No voluntary transfer of the rights or obligations of any party shall be made without the written content and approval of the other party except to a successor in operation of the properties of any party. Any successor or assignee of the rights of any party, whether by voluntary transfer, judicial or foreclosure sale or otherwise, shall be subject to all of the provisions and conditions of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff to the same extent as though such successor or assignee were the original party to this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, and no assignment or transfer of any right shall be effective unless and until the assignee or transferee agrees in writing to assume all of the obligations of the assignor or transferor and to be bound by all of the provisions and conditions of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff. The consent of Customer is hereby given to any security assignment or other like financing instrument which may be required under terms of any mortgage, trust, security agreement or other instrument or indebtedness made by and between PSE and any mortgagee, trustee, secured party, subsidiary of PSE or holder of such instrument of indebtedness, as security for bonds or other indebtedness of PSE, present or future; such mortgagee, trustee, secured party, subsidiary, or bolder may realize upon such security in foreclosure or other suitable proceedings, and succeed to any right, title and interests of PSE.

9. APPROVALS AND REGULATORY RULINGS This Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff is subject to valid laws, orders, rules and regulations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction over this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, PSE, the Customer or any of them. Nothing contained in this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff shall give the Commission jurisdiction over parties not otherwise subject to such jurisdiction or be construed as a grant of jurisdiction over any party by any state or federal agency not otherwise having jurisdiction by law.

8. BILLING AND PAYMENT 8.1 Billing Date After commencement of deliveries, PSE shall use its best efforts to bin on or before the tenth (10th) day of each month following the month of service. The Customer shall pay each bill on or before the twenty-fifth (25th) day of the month following the month of service for which the receiving party is being billed. If the twenty-fifth (25th) day of the month is a holiday or weekend, payment will be made on the last workday prior to the 25th day of the month. 8.2 Payment Address All payments to PSE shall be by electronic funds transfer to: Seattle First National Bank (ABA #125000024) for credit to Puget Sound Energy; Inc. Account No. 68634518 8.3 Due Date Bills which are not paid in full by the receiving party when due shall thereafter bear interest at the rate of 1.5% per month or at the maximum rate of interest allowed by law, whichever is less. 8.4 Cancellation of Service Agreement for Non-Payment PSE shall have the unilateral right to cancel the service agreement (and any transaction committed to under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff and any service agreement) of any Customer that is more than sixty (60) days delinquent in the payment of bills to PSE by filing with the Commission a notice of cancellation; provided, however, that any obligations of the Customer to PSE that were unperformed by the Customer prior to PSE's notice of cancellation of the service agreement shall be preserved until satisfied. 8.5 Creditworthiness PSE may implement reasonable credit review procedures in order to determine the ability of any Customer under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff to meet its obligations to PSE. This review shall be made in conformance with accepted commercial practices. In addition, PSE may require the Customer to provide and maintain in effect, during the term of the service agreement, an unconditional and irrevocable letter of credit as security to meet its responsibilities and obligations under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff. At the request of the Customer, PSE may consider alternative forms of security that are consistent with commercial practices established by the Uniform Commercial Code and that adequately protect PSE against risk of nonperformance by the Customer. If Customer fails to provide to PSE assurances satisfactory to PSE in its sole discretion, of Customer's ability to perform a transaction under this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff within three (3) business days of demand by PSE for such satisfactory assurance, PSE (in addition to exercising any and all remedies available at law or in equity, including but not limited to withholding, setting off against or recouping from amounts otherwise due) (i) may suspend performance of the transaction, or (ii) immediately terminate the transaction.

12. CUSTOMER OBLIGATIONS Customer assumes all responsibility for meeting tariff obligations associated with Transmission Rights over Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Provider’s Transmission System reassigned to Customer by PSE’s Wholesale Merchant Function (including, without limitation, scheduling requirements, posting requirements and procedures related to requests for changes in points of receipt or points of delivery.)

11. SEVERABILITY In the event that any of the terms, covenants or conditions of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff or the application of any such term, covenant or condition, shall be held invalid as to any person or circumstance by any court having jurisdiction, all other terms, covenants or conditions of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff and their application shall not be affected thereby, but shall remain in full force and effect unless a court holds that the provisions are not separable from all other provisions of this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff.

3. RATES Pursuant to this Electric Transmission Reassignment Tariff, the Wholesale Merchant Function shall resell, reassign, or transfer any Transmission Rights on a Non-Jurisdictional Transmission Providers Transmission System to a Customer at a price mutually agreed to between the Wholesale Merchant Function and Customer.
